\author{maxsnew}
\title{Extended Natural Numbers}

\def\extnat{#{\mathbb{N}_\infty}}

\p{The extended natural numbers \extnat are the final coalgebra for the functor #{X \mapsto X \uplus 1} in the category of sets. Concretely these can be constructed as monotone functions from #{\mathbb{N}} to the booleans. Since the natural numbers are the initial algebra for the same functor we get an canonical injective function #{\mathbb{N} \to \extnat}. We say an extended natural number is \em{finite} if it is in the image of this function.}

\p{In classical mathematics, the extended natural numbers are simply a coproduct of the natural numbers with a single "infinite" point. Constructively, we can define a function #{\mathbb{N} \uplus 1 \to \mathbb{N} \to \extnat} and it being an isomorphism is one of the formulations of [Markov's principle](QCIE).}